## âœ… what i did  
I'VE SOLVED THE CHALLENGE IN 3different WAYS:
I WAY cURL
-clicked start
-opened the terminal
-ran: 'cat /challenge/server'
found out i had to send a post request with token=srcmbctb @ /authenticate w/ User-Agent: Firefox and Host: challenge.localhost:80
-ran: '/challenge/server'
-ran: 'curl -v \'
      '-H "Host: challenge.localhost:80"  \'
      '-H "User-Agent: Firefox" \'
      '-d "token=srcmbctb" \'
      'http://challenge.localhost/authenticate'
-flag popped out

II WAY python
-clicked start
-opened the terminal
-ran: 'cat /challenge/server'
found out i had to send a post request with token=srcmbctb @ /authenticate w/ User-Agent: Firefox and Host: challenge.localhost:80
-ran: '/challenge/server'
-ran: 'vim bro'
-typed: '#!/usr/bin/env python3'
        'import requests'
        'url = "http://challenge.localhost/authenticate"'
        'headers = {'
            '"Host": "challenge.localhost:80",'
            '"User-Agent": "Firefox"'
        '}'
        'data = {'
            '"token": "srcmbctb"'
        '}'
        'r = requests.post(url, headers=headers, data=data)'
        'print(r.text)'
-ran: 'chmod a+x bro'
-ran: './bro'
-flag popped out

III WAY netcat
-clicked start
-opened the terminal
-ran: 'cat /challenge/server'
found out i had to send a post request with token=srcmbctb @ /authenticate w/ User-Agent: Firefox and Host: challenge.localhost:80
-ran: '/challenge/server'
-ran: 'nc -v challenge.localhost 80'
-typed: 'POST /authenticate HTTP/1.1'
        'Host: challenge.localhost:80'
        'User-Agent: Firefox'
        'Content-Type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded'
        'Content-Length: 14'
        ''
        'token=srcmbctb'
-flag popped out

## ğŸ§‘ğŸ¾â€ğŸ« what this challenge teaches u
a lot in each way
cURL -> \ allow to press enter w/out sending the command, -d flag is for body
python -> body has to be passed into data parameter
netcat -> u can unlock the body only by crafting the 2 follow headers: Content-Type and Content-Length (this one super crucial)

to check which process is using a port use: sudo ss -tulnp or sudo netstat -tulnp

